  "title": "Vibrations in Mechanical Systems",
  "body": " Vibrations in Mechanical Systems   Consider a spring that resists compression as well as extension, that is suspended vertically from a fixed support, and a body of mass that is attached at the lower end of the spring. We make the assumption that the mass is much larger than the mass of the spring so that we can neglect the mass of the spring. If there is no motion then the system is in static equilibrium, as illustrated in Figure . If the mass is pulled down further and released, then it will undergo an oscillatory motion.   The spring mass system    Suppose there is no friction to slow down the motion of the mass, then we say that the system is undamped . We will determine the motion of this mechanical system by considering the forces acting on the mass during the motion. This will lead to a differential equation relating the displacement as a function of time. The most obvious force is that of gravitational attraction acting on the mass and is given by , where is the acceleration of gravity. The next force to be considered is the spring force acting on the mass and is directed upward if the spring is stretched and downward if it is compressed. It obeys Hooke's law , where is the amount the spring is stretched when and is the amount it is compressed when .  When the system is in static equilibrium and the spring is stretched by the amount , the resultant of the spring force and the gravitational force is zero, which is expressed by the equation .  Let denote the displacement from static equilibrium with the positive direction pointed downward as indicated in Figure 10.17(b).The spring force can be written as , and the resultant force is .  The differential equation for motion is obtained by using Newton's second law, which states that the resultant of the forces acting on the mass at any instant satisfies .  The distance from equilibrium at time is measured by , so the acceleration is given by . Equations and then give   Therefore, the undamped mechanical system is governed by the linear differential equation .  The general solution to undamped system is known to be     Damped System  If we consider frictional forces that slow down the motion of the mass, then we say that the system is damped. This is visualized by connecting a dashpot to the mass, as indicated in Figure . For small velocities it is assumed that the frictional force is proportional to the velocity, that is,    The spring mass dashpot system    The damping constant must be positive, for if , then the mass is moving downward and hence must point upward, which requires that is negative. The result of the three forces acting on the mass is given by , so the damped mechanical system is governed by the differential equation .    Forced Vibrations  The vibration discussed earlier are called free vibrations because all the forces that affect the motion of the system are internal to the system. We extend our analysis to cover the case in which an external force acts on the mass (see Figure ). Such a force might occur from vibrations of the support to which the top of the spring is attached, or from the effect of a magnetic field on a mass made of iron. As before, we sum the forces , , , and and set this equal to the resultant force and obtain    The dashpot system with an external force    Thus, the forced motion of the mechanical system satisfies the nonhomogeneous linear differential equation .  The function is called the input or driving force and the solution is called the output or response . Of particular interest are periodic inputs that can be represented by Fourier series.  For damped mechanical systems that are driven by a periodic input , the general solution involves a transient part that vanishes as , and a steady state part that is periodic. The transient part of the solution is found by solving the homogeneous differential equation .  This homogeneous equation has the characteristic equation , and it's roots are . The coefficients , , and are all positive, and there are three cases to consider.   If , the roots are real and distinct, and since , it follows that the roots and are negative real numbers. Thus, for this case, we have .    If ,the roots are real and equal, then , where is a negative real number. Again, for this case we find that .    If , the roots are complex, then , where and are positive real numbers, and it follows that .   In all three cases, we see that the homogeneous solution decays to as . The steady state solution can be obtained by representing by its Fourier series and substituting , , and into the nonhomogeneous differential equation and solving the resulting system for the Fourier coefficients of . The general solution to Equation is then given by     Find the general solution to , where is given by the Fourier series .    First we solve for the transient solution. The characteristic equation is , which has a double root . Hence . The steady state solution is obtained by assuming that has the Fourier series representation , and that and can be obtained by termwise differentiation: .  Substituting these expansions into the differential equation results in .    Equating the coefficients with the given series for , we find that , and that .  Solving this linear system for and , we find that   The general solution is given by .   Exercises   For the exercises in this section solve for given the following Fourier series for .   , where for .   , where    , shown in Figure .   , shown in Figure .  Graph of for the exercises    Graph of for the exercises {0.5\\linewidth}   \\begin{task} .  \\begin{task}[(a)]    , , .  \\begin{task}[(c)] , , .  \\begin{task}[(c)] Alternative Answer:  Alternative Answer:   ,  .     .     .  \\begin{task}[(a)]  \\begin{task}[(c)]   , , .    , , .  \\begin{task}[(c)] Alternative Answer:  Alternative Answer:  ,  .     "
